      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Queensland First Home Owner Grant: What Brisbane Sellers Need to Know About FHOG Buyers
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        The Queensland FHOG does not apply to established homes. Understanding which incentives actually affect the buyer pool for your property will help you set a more accurate price and anticipate buyer behaviour.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>One of the more persistent misconceptions among Brisbane sellers is that the Queensland First Home Owner Grant (FHOG) creates a meaningful pool of additional buyers for established residential property. It does not. The grant is available only to buyers of new or substantially renovated homes, not to buyers of existing properties, which covers almost all residential resales in Brisbane's inner east. Understanding exactly who benefits from the FHOG, who does not, and what incentives actually do affect the buyer pool for a typical established home will help you form a more accurate view of your market.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the Queensland FHOG is and who it is for</h2>
      <p>The Queensland First Home Owner Grant is a one-off payment from the Queensland government to eligible first home buyers who purchase or build a new home. To receive the grant, the property must be a new home (never previously occupied as a place of residence) or a substantially renovated home (meeting specific criteria under the First Home Owner Grant Act 2000 (Qld)). The buyer must be an Australian citizen or permanent resident, must not have previously owned residential property in Australia, and must intend to live in the home as their principal place of residence for a continuous period of at least one year following settlement.</p>

      <p>The grant amount and any applicable value cap are set by the Queensland government and are periodically reviewed. In most circumstances, the FHOG has applied to properties valued below a threshold set in the legislation. Buyers and sellers should check the current grant amount and value cap on the Queensland Revenue Office website, as these figures can change.</p>

      <p>The key point for sellers of established Brisbane homes is simple: a buyer purchasing your property is not eligible for the FHOG regardless of whether they are a first home buyer, because the property is an established dwelling that has been previously occupied. The grant does not apply to your sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">First home buyers can still purchase your established home</h2>
      <p>The absence of the FHOG does not mean first home buyers are excluded from purchasing established properties. They are active participants in the established housing market and represent a meaningful share of buyers in certain price ranges, particularly below $800,000 in Brisbane's inner east. What they do not receive when buying an established home is the FHOG payment.</p>

      <p>First home buyers purchasing established properties may still receive other government assistance. The transfer duty (stamp duty) concession available in Queensland to first home buyers of established properties up to $700,000 is a meaningful benefit for buyers in that price range. They may also access the federal First Home Guarantee, which allows eligible buyers to purchase with a 5% deposit without paying lenders mortgage insurance, and potentially the Regional First Home Buyer Guarantee or other targeted schemes that are periodically introduced. These incentives lower the buyer's upfront costs and can expand the pool of buyers who are able to purchase in a given price range, even without the FHOG.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the transfer duty concession affects your buyer pool</h2>
      <p>Queensland's transfer duty (stamp duty) concession for first home buyers of established homes applies to properties with a dutiable value up to $700,000. Below this threshold, eligible first home buyers pay reduced or no transfer duty. Above $700,000, the full transfer duty rate applies and no concession is available.</p>

      <p>For sellers with properties priced around this threshold, the concession has a real but limited effect on buyer behaviour. A first home buyer who qualifies for the full concession on a property at $699,000 saves a meaningful amount relative to the same purchase at $701,000. This can make properties priced just below the threshold slightly more competitive among first home buyers than those priced just above it. In practice, this effect is most relevant for properties in the $600,000 to $800,000 range, where first home buyers are a material share of the buyer pool.</p>

      <p>For properties above $1 million, which describes a large portion of Brisbane inner-east stock, the transfer duty concession has no practical effect on the buyer pool or negotiation dynamics, because first home buyers are not typically the competing buyers at that price point regardless of the incentive structure.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The First Home Guarantee and its effect on your campaign</h2>
      <p>The federal First Home Guarantee (formerly the First Home Loan Deposit Scheme) allows eligible first home buyers to purchase with a deposit as low as 5% without paying lenders mortgage insurance. The government guarantees the remaining portion of the typical 20% deposit requirement, reducing the upfront cash the buyer needs to save. This scheme has property price caps that vary by location and are updated regularly.</p>

      <p>For sellers, the guarantee matters because it expands the pool of buyers who can genuinely proceed to finance at a given price point without needing the full 20% deposit saved. A buyer who is eligible for the First Home Guarantee and has a 5% deposit is a legitimate buyer if they can service the loan; without the guarantee they would need to save significantly more or pay LMI, which increases the loan cost. In markets where a significant share of buyers are first-time purchasers, this scheme has contributed to buyer capacity at certain price points.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical implication for Brisbane sellers: know your buyer profile</h2>
      <p>The most useful takeaway from understanding the FHOG and related incentives is that seller assumptions about their buyer pool should be grounded in facts about who actually purchases in their suburb and price range, not in general impressions about first home buyer activity.</p>

      <p>In Brisbane's inner-east suburbs at price points above $900,000, the primary buyers are typically owner-occupiers upgrading within the corridor, equity-rich sellers from neighbouring suburbs, and in some cases interstate buyers relocating to Brisbane. First home buyers are active participants in the market but are concentrated in the lower price brackets. Government incentives like the FHOG, the transfer duty concession, and the First Home Guarantee shape buyer activity in specific price ranges but have limited relevance to sellers at the top of the inner-east market.</p>

      <p>Your agent should be able to tell you what proportion of buyers in your suburb and price range in the past 12 months have been first home buyers, upgraders, or investors. That information is a better guide to your actual buyer pool than any general statement about government incentives.</p>

